Guest: Hello, I''d like to book a room for three nights, from the 15th to the 18th of next month.
Receptionist: Let me check availability. For those dates, we have a double room available on the 8th floor with a city view.
Guest: That sounds nice. What''s the rate?
Receptionist: It''s 1.2 million dong per night, and that includes breakfast for two.
Guest: Does it include anything else, like airport transfer?
Receptionist: I''m afraid the airport transfer is an additional charge. But breakfast is included in the room rate.
Guest: Alright, I''ll take it.
Receptionist: Wonderful. Could I have your passport number to complete the reservation?
Guest: Sure, let me get it.', 9);
Candidate: Yes, that''s right. I''m very interested in the role.
Interviewer: I can see you have about two years of experience in digital marketing. Can you tell me about your previous role?
Candidate: I worked at a small agency where I managed social media accounts and helped create content for various clients.
Interviewer: That''s good experience. For this position, we really emphasize communication skills, as you''ll be working directly with clients and presenting campaign ideas.
Candidate: I understand. In my previous role, I regularly presented reports to clients, so I''m comfortable with that.
Interviewer: Excellent. We have a few more candidates to interview. We''ll announce the results next week by email.
Candidate: Thank you. I look forward to hearing from you.', 10);
Patient: I have had a terrible headache for three days and I feel dizzy sometimes.
Doctor: I see. Have you been sleeping well?
Patient: Not really. I have been working very long hours this week.
Doctor: That could be the cause. I would like to check your blood pressure. It seems slightly elevated. I am going to prescribe some medication and I strongly recommend you take a few days off work.
Patient: Is it serious?
Doctor: Not at this stage, but if you continue at this pace, it could become a problem. I would also suggest reducing your caffeine intake and drinking more water.
Patient: How long should I take the medication?
Doctor: For one week. Come back and see me if the headaches do not improve.', 8);
Tenant: Yes, ideally near the city center and within my budget of 8 million dong per month.
Agent: I have a lovely apartment on Nguyen Hue Street. It is on the fifth floor with a great view. The rent is 7.5 million per month.
Tenant: That sounds good. Is it furnished?
Agent: Yes, fully furnished with air conditioning in all rooms. Utilities are not included though.
Tenant: What about parking?
Agent: There is one parking space included. Additional spaces cost 500,000 dong per month.
Tenant: When is it available?
Agent: From the first of next month. You would need to pay two months deposit upfront.
Tenant: I would like to view it this weekend if possible.
Agent: Of course. How about Saturday at 10 AM?', 9);

The movement has gained momentum for several reasons. First, it addresses food security concerns in densely populated cities. By producing food locally, cities can reduce their dependence on long supply chains that are vulnerable to disruption. During the COVID-19 pandemic, for example, many urban farms played a crucial role in supplying fresh produce when distribution networks were strained.

Second, urban farming has environmental benefits. It reduces the carbon footprint associated with transporting food over long distances. Green roofs and vertical gardens also help regulate building temperatures, reducing energy consumption for heating and cooling.

Third, urban farms create community spaces. Community gardens bring residents together, provide educational opportunities for children, and can improve mental health by connecting people with nature.

However, urban farming faces significant challenges. Land in cities is expensive and scarce. Water usage can be high. And the scale of production is generally too small to feed entire urban populations. Urban farming is best understood as a supplement to, rather than a replacement for, conventional agriculture.

Despite these limitations, the future of urban farming looks promising. Advances in vertical farming technology, hydroponics, and LED lighting are making indoor food production increasingly efficient and cost-effective.', 12);
Employee: Yes, I am sorry to bring this up, but I feel my contributions to the project are not being acknowledged.
Manager: Can you give me a specific example?
Employee: Last week, I developed the entire marketing strategy, but in the presentation to the board, only my colleague was credited.
Manager: I see. That does sound frustrating. Did you speak to your colleague about this?
Employee: I tried, but they said it was an oversight and it would not happen again.
Manager: I appreciate you bringing this to me. Going forward, I will ensure that all team contributions are properly documented and credited. I will also speak with your colleague.
Employee: Thank you. I just want to be recognized for my work.
Manager: That is completely reasonable. Let us schedule a team meeting next week to establish clearer guidelines for project attribution.', 9);

Researchers distinguish between two types of happiness. Hedonic happiness refers to the experience of pleasure and the absence of pain. Eudaimonic happiness refers to a deeper sense of meaning, purpose, and fulfillment. Studies suggest that eudaimonic happiness is more strongly associated with long-term well-being.

One of the most robust findings in happiness research is the importance of social connections. People with strong relationships consistently report higher levels of happiness than those who are socially isolated. The Harvard Study of Adult Development, which followed participants for over 80 years, found that the quality of relationships was the single strongest predictor of happiness and health in old age.

Money does have some relationship with happiness, but the effect is more limited than most people assume. Research suggests that happiness increases with income up to a point where basic needs and security are met, but beyond that, additional wealth has diminishing returns on well-being.

Gratitude practices have been shown to significantly boost happiness. People who regularly write down things they are grateful for report higher levels of positive emotion and life satisfaction. Exercise is another powerful happiness booster, with studies showing effects comparable to antidepressant medication for mild to moderate depression.

The good news is that happiness is not entirely determined by genetics or circumstances. Research suggests that approximately 40% of our happiness is within our control through intentional activities and mindset.', 11);
Customer: Hi, I am planning a trip to Japan for two weeks in April. Can you help me with a package?
Agent: Absolutely. We have an excellent 14-day package that includes flights, hotels, and a guided tour of Tokyo, Kyoto, and Osaka.
Customer: That sounds great. What is the price?
Agent: The standard package is 45 million dong per person, including all accommodation and breakfast daily.
Customer: Does it include the bullet train between cities?
Agent: Yes, the Shinkansen pass is included. You would need to budget separately for lunches, dinners, and personal shopping.
Customer: What about travel insurance?
Agent: We strongly recommend it. We can arrange comprehensive travel insurance for an additional 2 million dong.
Customer: I will need to discuss it with my partner first. Can I call back tomorrow?
Agent: Of course. I will hold the current pricing until Friday.', 8);
Professor: Of course, come in. What seems to be the problem?
Student: Well, I just realized that my Biology lab and my English class are at the same time on Wednesdays. There''s a schedule conflict.
Professor: I see. Have you checked if there are other sections available for either course?
Student: I looked, but the only other Biology section is already full.
Professor: In that case, I''d suggest you change to a different English section. There should be openings in the Tuesday-Thursday section.
Student: Oh, that would work! When is the deadline to make changes?
Professor: You have until next week to submit the change request through the online portal.
Student: Thank you so much, Professor. I''m really relieved. I was worried I''d have to drop one of the courses.
Professor: No problem. Just make sure you complete the change before the deadline.', 8);
Activist: Of course. We started the Green Neighborhood Initiative three years ago. Our main goal is to reduce plastic waste in our local area.
Interviewer: What specific actions have you taken?
Activist: We have organized monthly clean-up events, installed recycling stations in the neighborhood, and run educational workshops in local schools.
Interviewer: What has been the biggest challenge?
Activist: Getting people to change their habits. Many residents understand the problem intellectually but find it difficult to change their daily routines.
Interviewer: Have you seen measurable results?
Activist: Yes, we have reduced plastic waste in our area by approximately 40% over three years. We have also inspired three neighboring communities to start similar initiatives.
Interviewer: What are your plans for the future?
Activist: We want to expand our school program and work with local businesses to eliminate single-use plastics entirely.', 10);
Advisor: Let me check your account. What is your student ID?
